\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Analysis of The Motion of \alert{A Falling Body}}
\framesubtitle{1: The Basic Setup}
\label{slide:analysis-of-falling-body}

\begin{columns}[c]
\column{.7\textwidth}
\alert{Consider a Falling Stone.} 

Its Motion Is Described by Giving Its Position (Displacement from A Reference) as A Function of Time. \alert{As It Falls, Its Velocity Increases}, So That The \alert{Velocity at Each Instant Is Also A Variable Function of Time}.  Newton Called \alert{The \textit{Instantaneous Position} Function The `Fluent'} And \alert{The \textit{Instantaneous Velocity} Function the `Fluxion'}. 

If One Is Given, The Other Can Be Determined; \alert{This Connection Is The Heart of The Infinitesimal Calculus Fashioned by Newton and Leibniz}.
\column{.3\textwidth}
\def\scale{0.4}
\def\xtime{0}
\def\xdisp{2}
\def\xvel{4}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=\scale]
\draw (\xtime,-17cm) node[red] {\tiny{$t$(s)}};
\draw (\xdisp,-17cm) node[red] {\tiny{$d$(m)}};
\draw[thin] (\xtime,0) -- (\xtime,-16.5);
\draw[thin] (\xdisp,0) -- (\xdisp,-16.5);
\foreach \y in {1,2,3,4} {
  \def\sq{\y*\y}
  \pgfmathparse{4.9*\y*\y}
  \draw (-2pt,-\sq) -- (2pt,-\sq) node[anchor=east] {\tiny \y};
  \draw (\xdisp,-\sq) -- (\xdisp,-\sq) node[anchor=east] {\tiny{\pgfmathresult}};
  \draw (\xdisp+0.3,-\sq) ellipse [x radius=6pt, y radius=3pt];
}
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{columns}
\end{frame}
